Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.
Additions to the Complex, including the small reservoir, the bathroom and the anteroom.

Locus 22 is the low bench feature in the west of the bench room. This feature really should not be called a bench, but there is nothing in particular that does readily define this feature, and as this was the term given to it in the field it will continue to be referred to this way for consistency (perhaps a term like low wall would have been better). The locus consists of a single row of rough-hewn sandstone ashlars that follows the outline of the west and north walls of the bench room. It is not flush with these walls, but instead is a slight distance from it, with soil between the walls and the bench. The floor of the room (Locus 10) is cut to fit this feature. The locus is approximately 27 cm thick, and is between 5 cm and 22 cm above the floor. The north part of the bench extends east-west, following the wall, and is 1.23 m long. The central section extends north-south and is 2.40 m long. The south section (0.68 m) turns again to extend east-west and meets Locus 6 just north of the doorway. This feature is quite enigmatic, and cannot be explained without further excavation. Perhaps digging through the dirt between the bench and the walls will clarify its purpose. It could, for example, be some sort of long fountain or trough, or it could have been built up higher to create this supposed bench. It could have been a lower structural support for a system of wooden benches and cubbies for patrons of the baths to store their belongings in, making the room a possible apodyterium. For these benches to have been in use, the doorway in the south of the room (Locus 19), would have to be blocked (Locus 20). These features of the 'bench room' are therefore all phased to Stage 3.
